pullRequest.body:
This does a few things:
- Define the algebra morphism `TrivSqZeroExt.map f` between trivial square-zero extensions induced by a linear map`f`, and establish some of its basic properties (functoriality, composition with the basic maps to/from `TrivSqZeroExt`). Note that we only consider the case of a commutative base ring, because the case of a general base ring requires morphisms of bimodules, which we do not have.
- Define the algebra morphism `ExteriorAlgebra.map f` between exterior algebras induced by a linear map `f`. This is a straightforward application of the similar construction for Clifford algebras, but I think it is still useful to have. Basic properties of this construction are proved: functoriality, composition with `ExteriorAlgebra.ι`, `ExteriorAlgebra.ιInv` (this part uses the first point) and `ExteriorAlgebra.ιMulti`. Then exactness properties of the construction is studied:
  - If the linear map is surjective, then the map on exterior algebras is also surjective. This actually holds for Clifford algebras, so I added a lemma called `CliffordAlgebra.map_surjective` in `LinearAlgebra/CliffordAlgebra/Basic.lean`. For exterior algebras, the converse holds and is also proved.
  - If the linear map has a retraction, then the map on exterior algebras is injective. So if the base ring is a field, the map on exterior algebras is injective if the linear map is injective.

- Establish some properties of `ExteriorAlgebra.ιMulti`:
  - `ExteriorAlgebra.ιMulti_range`: The range of `ιMulti R n` is contained in the `n`th exterior power (define here as `LinearMap.range (ι R : M →ₗ[R] ExteriorAlgebra R M) ^ n`).
  - `ExteriorAlgebra.ιMulti_span_fixedDegree`: This range spans the `n`th exterior power.
  - `ExteriorAlgebra.ιMulti_span`: The union over all `n` of the range of `ιMulti R n` spans the whole exterior algebra (this is in `LinearAlgebra/ExteriorAlgebra/Grading.lean` because the proof uses the graded module structure, but it might be possible to do something simpler).

- Construct `ExteriorAlgebra.ιMulti_family`: This takes a natural number `n` and a family of vectors `v` indexed by a linearly ordered type `I`, and it returns the family of `n`-fold products of the `v i` in the exterior algebra, indexed by the set of finsets of `I` of cardinality `n`. (The point, to be proved in another PR, is that when `v` is a basis, then `ExteriorAlgebra.ιMulti_family R n v` is a basis of the `n`th exterior power.)

```suggestion
maps it induces between Clifford algebras is also surjective.-/
```

I think this is just making work for yourself; can't you work with the definition of `Surjective` directly?
I can. I also rewrote the proof using `CliffordAlgebra.induction` as you suggested.
You should be able to use `induction y using CliffordAlgebra.induction` here
Note that you should never write `.carrier`, but should write a coercion to a `Set` instead.
Okay, but I ran into trouble with the power, and the only way I found out of it was to coerce to `Submodule`, raise to the `n`th power then coerce to `Set`.
Does writing `(LinearMap.range (ι R : M →ₗ[R] ExteriorAlgebra R M) ^ n :)` work? (with the 🙂 at the end)

No, I get
```
type mismatch
  LinearMap.range (ι R) ^ n
has type
  Submodule R (ExteriorAlgebra R M) : outParam (Type (max u1 u2))
but is expected to have type
  Set (ExteriorAlgebra R ?m.262794) : Type (max u1 ?u.262791)
```
I pushed a fix; the issue was on the LHS!
Wow, black magic. Thanks !

I think it's probably worth having a lemma that conclude `LeftInverse (map f) (map g)` from `LeftInverse f g`, which is essential what you prove after the `by` here

(I think using `LeftInverse` to prove injectivity is slightly more idiomatic than `RightInverse`, looking at how `RightInverse.injective` is a shorthand for `LeftInverse.injective`)
Will do tomorrow, I really need to go to bed now.

I wrote the lemma about left inverses. For the linear maps, I'm keeping the "left inverse" condition as `g.comp f = LinearMap.id` rather than `LeftInverse g f`, because this is the condition that [LinearMap.exists_leftInverse_of_injective](https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/LinearAlgebra/Basis/VectorSpace.html#LinearMap.exists_leftInverse_of_injective) gives me in its conclusion, so it makes the lemma easier to use for modules over a field.
This is computable :)

This will be more pleasant to unfold as 
```suggestion
  fun s ↦ ιMulti R n (fun i => v (Finset.orderIsoOfFin _ s.prop i))
```
at which point you may as well move the `s` behind the colon.

A little easier to read with fewer parens, perhaps:
```suggestion
    Submodule.span R (Set.range fun x : Σ n, (Fin n → M) => ιMulti R x.1 x.2) = ⊤ := by
```

Golfed:
```suggestion
  rw [Submodule.eq_top_iff']
  intro x
  induction x
    using DirectSum.Decomposition.inductionOn fun i => LinearMap.range (ι R (M := M)) ^ i with
  | h_zero => exact Submodule.zero_mem _
  | h_add _ _ hm hm' => exact Submodule.add_mem _ hm hm'
  | h_homogeneous hm =>
    let ⟨m, hm⟩ := hm
    apply Set.mem_of_mem_of_subset hm
    rw [← ιMulti_span_fixedDegree]
    refine Submodule.span_mono fun _ hx ↦ ?_
    obtain ⟨y, rfl⟩ := hx
    exact ⟨⟨_, y⟩, rfl⟩
```

```suggestion
    LinearMap.range (ι R : M →ₗ[R] ExteriorAlgebra R M) ^ n := by
```

nit:

```suggestion
/-- An injective morphism of vector spaces induces an injective morphism of exterior algebras. -/
```
(throughout)
Like so ?
I pushed a change here to turn this into a `Iff`; are any of your other results amenable to the same strengthening?
`ExteriorAlgebra.map_surjective` is an `Iff`, but the best way I see to prove it would to first prove that `ιInv` and `map f` compose to `f`.
That sounds like a nice result to have, but I think it's fair to declare it out of scope for this PR.
I'm seeing if I can do an easy proof. If I fail, then I'll agree with you.
Can you prove this for `CliffordAlgebra` too?
Oh, it's not true (in general)!

One direction is very easy (and has the same proof as for the exterior algebra). The other direction is true if [CliffordAlgebra.ι](https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/LinearAlgebra/CliffordAlgebra/Basic.html#CliffordAlgebra.%CE%B9) is injective, which I thought was true but I'm not used to Clifford algebras (especially over general rings), so who knows. 
When I first wrote the injectivity lemma, I decided against having a Clifford algebra version because my goal was "over a field, `map f` is injective if `f` is injective", which is false in general. But it would be quite easy to add at least one direction of the lemma above for Clifford algebras, if you think that has value (I am not sure myself).
I think it's worth having one direction of the result, simply because it shortens the proof here.

> The other direction is true if [CliffordAlgebra.ι](https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/LinearAlgebra/CliffordAlgebra/Basic.html#CliffordAlgebra.%CE%B9) is injective, which I thought was true but I'm not used to Clifford algebras

This is true whenever `Q` is induced by a bilinear form, though mathlib only actually states it (via `equivExterior`) for rings with an invertible 2. I have plans to tidy that up, as the proof would all work in the more general case.

I don't know if it's true if `Q` is not induced by a bilinear form.

> I think it's worth having one direction of the result, simply because it shortens the proof here.

Ok, just a second.

Done, thought probably not optimal.
As for the question of generalizing to Clifford algebras, I think it might be too ambitious for this PR.

Thanks!

I agree, the Iff version sounds like it belongs in a separate PR; and I have plans to refactor the "induced by bilinear form" condition anyway.

```suggestion
lemma leftInverse_map_of_leftInverse {Q₁ : QuadraticForm R M₁} {Q₂ : QuadraticForm R M₂} (f : Q₁ →qᵢ Q₂)
```

Could eliminte the `fun` here:
```suggestion
def ιMulti_family (n : ℕ) {I : Type*} [LinearOrder I] (v : I → M) (s : {s : Finset I // Finset.card s = n}) :
    ExteriorAlgebra R M :=
  ιMulti R n fun i => v (Finset.orderIsoOfFin _ s.prop i)
```
I'd be tempted to make this an `abbrev` rather than a `def`, especially since you include no theorems about it.
If it's an `abbrev`, no one needs any theorems because it because everything can see through it.
These two results should move to `TrivSqZeroExt.lean`

You were too fast for me, I was going to comment on that. This is just a "let's see if it works" version. I also need a better name for `mapTriv`, and presumably a version without the commutativity of `R` if it works the same way.
I moved the def and theorem. Morally these should also be done for a noncommutative base ring, but it would require `f` to be `R`-bilinear, not just `R`-linear, so it might complicate things.

I don't think this should be primed:
```suggestion
def map (f : M →ₗ[R'] N) : TrivSqZeroExt R' M →ₐ[R'] TrivSqZeroExt R' N := by
```
I think you can get here faster with `liftEquivOfComm`, unless I'm missing something.
Yes, much faster. I also wrote some `simp` lemmas.

```suggestion
/-- Functoriality of `TrivSqZeroExt` when the ring is commutative: a linear map
`f : M →ₗ[R'] N` induces a morphism of `R'`-algebras from `TrivSqZeroExt R' M` to
`TrivSqZeroExt R' N`.

Note that we cannot neatly state the non-commutative case, as we do not have morphisms of bimodules.
-/
```
I think it would be reasonable to add `section map` around all of these new results.

This statement is backwards with respect to its name.
```suggestion
    Function.Surjective (map f) ↔ Function.Surjective f := by
```
I'm not sure why, but ok.

`foo_iff` is how statements of the form `Foo ↔ Bar` are named. Statements of the form `Bar ↔ Foo ` are called `bar_iff` or `bar_iff_foo`.

In this case, putting the `map` on the left also makes this a nice `simp` lemma.
Ah, I see, thanks. I should actually make it a 'simp' lemma then.
Please mention this in the commit message
I updated the commit message.
